          "id": "philosophy-101-l05-c3",
          "title": "Utilitarianism: The Greatest Good for the Greatest Number",
          "content": "Utilitarianism is an important moral theory that was created by two influential philosophers, Jeremy Bentham and John Stuart Mill. This theory helps us think about how to make decisions by focusing on the outcomes of our actions. According to utilitarianism, the best action is the one that brings the most happiness to the largest number of people. This means that when we are faced with a choice, we should consider how our decision will affect everyone involved and try to choose the option that maximizes overall happiness.\nJeremy Bentham introduced a unique method called 'felicific calculus.' This method is a way to measure pleasure and pain by looking at seven different factors. These factors include intensity (how strong the pleasure or pain is), duration (how long it lasts), certainty (how likely it is to happen), propinquity (how soon it will occur), fecundity (the chance it has to lead to more pleasure), purity (the likelihood that it won’t lead to pain), and extent (how many people are affected). By considering all these aspects, Bentham believed we could make better moral choices.\nJohn Stuart Mill built upon Bentham's ideas by emphasizing that not all pleasures are equal. He made a distinction between higher pleasures, which include intellectual and artistic experiences, and lower pleasures, which are more about physical enjoyment. Mill argued that the quality of pleasure is more important than just the amount. He famously said, 'it is better to be Socrates dissatisfied than a fool satisfied,' suggesting that having deep, meaningful experiences is more valuable than simply seeking pleasure.\nHowever, some critics of utilitarianism raise important concerns. They argue that this approach can sometimes justify sacrificing the rights of an individual if it benefits the majority. This brings up significant questions about justice and whether it is fair to prioritize the happiness of the many over the rights of the few. To address these concerns, a variation called rule utilitarianism was developed. This approach suggests that instead of looking at individual actions, we should evaluate the rules that guide our actions to ensure they promote overall happiness without compromising individual rights.\nContext recap: Utilitarianism is an important moral theory that was created by two influential philosophers, Jeremy Bentham and John Stuart Mill. This theory helps us think about how to make decisions by focusing on the outcomes of our actions. According to utilitarianism, the best action is the one that brings the most happiness to the largest number of people. This means that when we are faced with a choice, we should consider how our decision will affect everyone involved and try to choose the option that maximizes overall happiness.\nWhy this matters: Utilitarianism: The Greatest Good for the Greatest Number helps learners in Philosophy connect ideas from Introduction to Philosophy to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nContext recap: Utilitarianism is an important moral theory that was created by two influential philosophers, Jeremy Bentham and John Stuart Mill. This theory helps us think about how to make decisions by focusing on the outcomes of our actions. According to utilitarianism, the best action is the one that brings the most happiness to the largest number of people. This means that when we are faced with a choice, we should consider how our decision will affect everyone involved and try to choose the option that maximizes overall happiness.\nWhy this matters: Utilitarianism: The Greatest Good for the Greatest Number helps learners in Philosophy connect ideas from Introduction to Philosophy to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification."
